482 ff. The statement here is not that Richard deliberately starved himself to death on hearing of the failure of the rising and the death of his associates, but that he lost hope and contage and could not eat, ‘quod vix si prandia sumit, Aut si sponte bibit vinum‚’ and that he desired the death which oeme to him. This is not an incredible account, and it is fairly in accordance with the best evidence. Most of the contemporary authorities give starvation as the cause, or one of the causes, of death, and the account of it given in our text agrees with that of Walsingham (ii. 245), Annales Henria‘ IV, p. 330, Eulog. Hist. contin. iii. 387. The Monk ovaesham mentions this commonly accepted story, but thinks it more probable that he was starved involun- tarily: ‘Aliter tamen dicitur et verius, quod ibidem fame miserabiliter interiit,’ and this is also the assertion of the Percies’ proclamation (Harding's Chronicle, ed. Ellis, p. 3 52). Creton says,

⁶ Apres le roy de ces nouvelles,

Qui ne furcnt bonnes ne belles,

En son cuer print de courroux tant, Que depuis celle heure en avant Oncques ne menga ne ne but,

Ains covint que la mort recut, Comme ilz dient; maiz vrayement Je ne croy pas ensement τ’

” and he proceeds to say that he rather believes that Richard is still alive in prison (Archaeologia, xx. p. 408). Adam of Usk (p. 41) says that Richard was brought almost to death by grief and the disappointment of his hopes, but that his death was partly caused by the scantiness of the food supplied to him. The Chronique de la Trae‘son tells the story about Piers Exton, which was afterwards commonly accepted by historiatis, but this was certainly not current at the time in England.

462 ff. The epithet ‘ pius} which Gower attaches to Henry's name in this passage, means in his mouth ‘ merciful,’ and in the margin the ‘ pietas ’ of the new king is contrasted with the ‘ cruelty ’ of Richard, the vice to which Gower chiefly attributes his fall. There is no doubt that the execution of Arundel and the murder of Gloucester (or the popular opinion that he had been murdered) produced a very sinister impression, and caused a general feeling of insecurity which was very favourable to Henry’s enterprise.
